https://prez.dev/label.@value: 1297.0 ANZSRC - Australian and New Zealand Standard Research Classification, 2020: Fields of Research (FoR)

https://prez.dev/description.@value: This group covers physical geography and environmental geoscience

A categorization of disciplines or topics that the broad field of Earth science can be subdivided into, i.e. a listing of the Fields of Research, or subjects, to which a geoscience dataset, publication, observation/activity, or entity pertains. The vocabulary also contains relevant disciplines that intersect with the various Earth science fields, such as biological sciences and built environment and design, as well as entries related to collection and heritage management. Notations included are those from the 2020 ANZSRC listing (see History Note) or in common use in the geoscience community.

The scientific study of the general configuration of the Earth's surface, i.e. of the origin and evolution of topographic and bathymetric features created by physical, chemical or biological processes operating at or near the Earth's surface. Specifically studies dealing with the classification, description, nature, origin, processes, and development of present landforms and their relationships to underlying structures, and of the history of geological changes as recorded by these surface features. Geomorphology overlaps in meaning with physiography, with 'physiography' commonly regarded as a more descriptive and 'geomorphology' as a more interpretative study of landforms.

The scientific discipline concerned with all aspects of ice and solid water on landmasses. It deals with the structure and properties of glaciers and ice sheets, their physical properties, formation and distribution, the dynamics of ice flow, and the interactions of ice accumulation with climate.

The area of geology that deals with the distribution and movement of subsurface water (i.e. groundwater) in the soil and rocks of the Earth's crust, and with related geological aspects of surface waters.

The study of natural phenomena that might have a negative effect on humans or the environment, specifically hazards encompassing geological and meteorological phenomena such as earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, wildfires, cyclonic storms, floods, droughts, avalanches and landslides, as well as phenomena such as natural radioactivity.

The study of climates prior to the period of instrumental records, and of the causes of their variation, on either a local, regional or worldwide basis. It uses a variety of proxy methods from the Earth and life sciences to obtain data preserved within rocks, sediments, ice sheets, tree rings, corals, shells, and microfossils to determine the past states of the Earth's various climate regions and its atmospheric system.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The branch of natural science which deals with the classification, form, processes, extent and patterns of natural phenomena in the natural environment such as the atmosphere, hydrosphere, biosphere, and geosphere. It differs chiefly from geology in that it considers conditions of the Earth primarily over shorter time scales (e.g. Quaternary and/or modern rates). It is more inclusive than geomorphology, dealing not only with landforms but also climate, oceans, atmosphere, soils, geologic processes, natural resources, and the biogeographical distribution of animal and plant life.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hist.@value: From the Fields of Research vocabulary from the Australian and New Zealand Standard Research Classification (ANZSRC, 2020). Definition adapted from Glossary of geology (5th edition revised; Neuendorf et al., 2011) and Wikipedia.

https://prez.dev/description.@value: Physical geographical and environmental science data and information not otherwise described by other sub-categories of physical geography.

The branch of geology that study environmental changes from 2.58 million years ago to the present. In particular, Quaternary geology study the process and deposits that developed during the Quaternary, a period characterized by glacial–interglacial cycles.

The study of the geology of surficial deposits, i.e. those at or near the Earth's surface. It includes the study of soils and unconsolidated sediments, their geological features and structures, and their relationships to the underlying bedrock.

The study of the form, physical properties, composition, function, and evolution of Earth’s surface, a dynamic interface where physical, chemical, biological, and human processes cause and are affected by forces in the Earth system, with impact-feedback loops that occur over a wide range of temporal and spatial scales.

The subfield of hydrology concerned with above-earth water, in contrast to groundwater hydrology that deals with water below the surface of the Earth. Its applications include rainfall and runoff, the routes that surface water takes (for example through rivers or reservoirs), and the occurrence of floods and droughts.
